revision 1.6
date: 2006/10/13 21:24:50;  author: talmage;  state: Exp;  lines: +9 -0
build.xml demands java 1.4.  This ensures that we use the same compiler on all development platforms.

revision 1.5
date: 2006/07/14 14:36:58;  author: talmage;  state: Exp;  lines: +43 -1


build.xml: I reorganized the JAR files to clearly separate SOUSA
classes from IDOL classes and utility classes from framework classes.

SOUSA.jar contains the classes from cmf/sousa, cmf/sousa/directory,
and cmf/sousa/spatiotemporal.

SOUSA_util.jar contains the classes from cmf/sousa/util.

IDOL.jar contains the classes from cmf/sousa/idol.

IDOL_util.jar contains the classes from cmf/sousa/idol/util.

IDOL_service.jar contains the classes from cmf/sousa/idol/service.

IDOL_user.jar contains the classes from cmf/sousa/idol/user.

Annotation.jar contains the classes from cmf/annotation
----------------------------
revision 1.4
date: 2006/04/03 15:46:40;  author: talmage;  state: Exp;  lines: +14 -8

build.xml: added property "javadoc.dir" with the value "docs/javadoc".
It's a subdirectory of "docs.dir" (value "docs").  The javadoc target
creates "javadoc.dir" and puts the javadoc output there.  The
clean_javadoc target removes "javadoc.dir" but not "docs.dir".

Makefile: no longer used or needed
----------------------------
revision 1.3
date: 2006/01/17 17:27:54;  author: talmage;  state: Exp;  lines: +12 -3
build.xml: new target, doccheck, places output in docs/doccheck.  From
the documentation: "DocCheck is an extension to the Javadoc tool that
reviews Javadoc comments in the source code, identifying gaps and
irregularities. It produces an HTML report that separates serious
problems from trivial ones, and makes "suggestions" in the form of
templates that show you what is needed. (Those suggestions can then be
copied into the code and edited.) DocCheck recursively examines
directories, and can be instructed to ignore packages and classes
using fully-qualified wildcard patterns. The utility package contains
a tool that scans a directory tree to generate a list of packages, as
well as pattern-matching classes for filenames."

package-template: Sun's template for package.html.  Copy to
${your-package-dir}/package.html and edit freely to provide
package-level documentation for each of your packages.
----------------------------

talmage.sage.cmf.nrl.navy.mil% cat idol.txt 


--------------------------------------------------------------
Contents

Problem I: SEARCH
Problem II: DYNAMIC DATA DELIVERY
Problem III: INFORMATION FUSION
Problem IV: INDIVIDUAL ACTION
Problem V: COLLABORATION
--------------------------------------------------------------



--------------------------------------------------------------
I: SEARCH, 
or how the client finds the server.
--------------------------------------------------------------

Scalability Axes:
(a) number of service types
(b) number of service instances
(c) number of clients instances

Scalable Solution Components: 

OPEN ONTOLOGIES: Each server advertises a set of ontologies, which
describe the information it can provide and the operations it can
support.  These programmatic ontologies are annotated by keywords and
human-readable descriptions.  This solution component addresses
scalability axis (a) number of service types.

HIERARCHICAL DIRECTORY SERVICE: There is a hierarchical directory
service which propagates afforementioned server ontology
advertisements.  This service is used to by clients to locate servers
which support particular ontologies.  Searches can also be conducted
using keywords and the content of human-readable descriptions.  This
solution component addresses scalability axes (b) and (c) the number
of service and client instances.


--------------------------------------------------------------
II: DYNAMIC DATA DELIVERY, 
or how the client gets information from the server.
--------------------------------------------------------------

Scalable Solution Components 

OPEN FRAMEWORK to support publishing arbitrary types of multisensory
data with spatiotemporal extents.  Initially we will support:
* raster data
* 3D terrain data,
* 3D models,
* video imagery,
* audio streams,
* sensor streams.

PERSISTENT QUERY.  Each client publishes a set of parameters to the
server--these parameters are treated as a dynamic specification of the
client's query to the server.  If either the server's data or the
client's query parameters change, the server efficiently sends the
client suitable updates.

In addition to application-specific parameters, a typical server will
consider the following generic parameters which could be part of the
client's query:

A. the client's spatiotemporal region of interest, 

   OPTIMIZATION FOR SPATIOTEMPORAL QUERIES.  There is a generic
   intrinsic support for servers to index data having spatiotemporal
   extents.  This system is optimized to support efficient search for
   items within within each clients' dynamic spatiotemporal region of
   interest.

B. the resolution/fidelity of information required,

   MULTI-RESOLUTION REPRESENTATIONS.  For particular types of data (2D
   rasters, 3D terrain maps, 3D geometric models) there is intrinsic
   support for servers to manage multiple resolutions.  This permits
   optimized support for items that are within each clients' dynamic
   spatiotemporal region of interest.
 
C. the capabilities of the client's hardware and properties of the
   network connecting the server to the client.

   HYBRID DSM/RPC: Information processing can take place either at
   server or at client.  In the DSM model, data is shipped to the
   client as a cached copy, while in the RPC model, the processing is
   done at the server.  Which model is used depends on the client's
   hardware and properties of the network connecting the server to the
   client, the relative size of the data being processed, the server
   load, etc.

D. the authenticated credentials of the client user.

   MODULAR SECURITY.


--------------------------------------------------------------
III: INFORMATION FUSION, 
or how the client synthesizes information from many servers.
--------------------------------------------------------------

Scalable Solution Components: 

FILTERING.  The results from each query can be filtered by the client
and added to the client's session.

DYNAMIC LAYER COMPOSITION.  The client can group the filtered results
from different servers into layers.  Within a layer, data can be
inter-connected using a network of prepositional connectives.  For
example, 2D rasters can be blended, then mapped onto 3D terrains.
Individual 3D geometries can be placed onto 3D terrains.  

INTER-LAYER LENSES.  The visual properties, translucency and rendering
order of layers can be manipulated.

OPEN PRESENTATION ARCHITECTURE.  Clients supported for platforms of
various capabilities, from handhelds to supercomputers.

IMMERSIVE PRESENTATION.  When available at the client, the set of all
layers is rendered using a high-performance 3D renderer.


--------------------------------------------------------------
Problem IV: INDIVIDUAL ACTION
How the client gets information from the server.
--------------------------------------------------------------

COMMAND INTERFACES.



--------------------------------------------------------------
Problem V: COLLABORATION
How the client gets information from the server.
--------------------------------------------------------------

CLIENTS AS SERVERS.

talmage@sousa:~/Work/postgis-1.1.6$ ./configure --help
`configure' configures this package to adapt to many kinds of systems.

Usage: ./configure [OPTION]... [VAR=VALUE]...

To assign environment variables (e.g., CC, CFLAGS...), specify them as
VAR=VALUE.  See below for descriptions of some of the useful variables.

Defaults for the options are specified in brackets.

Configuration:
  -h, --help              display this help and exit
      --help=short        display options specific to this package
      --help=recursive    display the short help of all the included packages
  -V, --version           display version information and exit
  -q, --quiet, --silent   do not print `checking...' messages
      --cache-file=FILE   cache test results in FILE [disabled]
  -C, --config-cache      alias for `--cache-file=config.cache'
  -n, --no-create         do not create output files
      --srcdir=DIR        find the sources in DIR [configure dir or `..']

Installation directories:
  --prefix=PREFIX         install architecture-independent files in PREFIX
                          [/usr/local]
  --exec-prefix=EPREFIX   install architecture-dependent files in EPREFIX
                          [PREFIX]

By default, `make install' will install all the files in
`/usr/local/bin', `/usr/local/lib' etc.  You can specify
an installation prefix other than `/usr/local' using `--prefix',
for instance `--prefix=$HOME'.

For better control, use the options below.

Fine tuning of the installation directories:
  --bindir=DIR           user executables [EPREFIX/bin]
  --sbindir=DIR          system admin executables [EPREFIX/sbin]
  --libexecdir=DIR       program executables [EPREFIX/libexec]
  --datadir=DIR          read-only architecture-independent data [PREFIX/share]
  --sysconfdir=DIR       read-only single-machine data [PREFIX/etc]
  --sharedstatedir=DIR   modifiable architecture-independent data [PREFIX/com]
  --localstatedir=DIR    modifiable single-machine data [PREFIX/var]
  --libdir=DIR           object code libraries [EPREFIX/lib]
  --includedir=DIR       C header files [PREFIX/include]
  --oldincludedir=DIR    C header files for non-gcc [/usr/include]
  --infodir=DIR          info documentation [PREFIX/info]
  --mandir=DIR           man documentation [PREFIX/man]

System types:
  --build=BUILD     configure for building on BUILD [guessed]
  --host=HOST       cross-compile to build programs to run on HOST [BUILD]

Optional Packages:
  --with-PACKAGE[=ARG]    use PACKAGE [ARG=yes]
  --without-PACKAGE       do not use PACKAGE (same as --with-PACKAGE=no)
  --without-iconv         disable unicode support
  --with-pgsql[=ARG]      build for a specific pgsql version
                          [ARG=path to pg_config]
  --with-geos[=ARG]       enable spatial predicates and operators using GEOS
                          [ARG=path to geos-config]
  --with-geos-libdir=PATH path to GEOS libdir
                          [taken from geos-config by default]
  --with-proj[=DIR]       enable reprojection support
  --with-proj-libdir=PATH path to PROJ4 libdir
  --with-jts[=ARG]        use JTS for spatial predicates and operators
                          [ARG=path to jts-config]
  --with-docdir=DIR       install the documentation in DIR [PREFIX/share/doc]

Some influential environment variables:
  CC          C compiler command
  CFLAGS      C compiler flags
  LDFLAGS     linker flags, e.g. -L<lib dir> if you have libraries in a
              nonstandard directory <lib dir>
  CPPFLAGS    C/C++ preprocessor flags, e.g. -I<include dir> if you have
              headers in a nonstandard directory <include dir>
  CXX         C++ compiler command
  CXXFLAGS    C++ compiler flags
  CPP         C preprocessor

Use these variables to override the choices made by `configure' or to help
it to find libraries and programs with nonstandard names/locations.

talmage@sousa:~/Work/postgis-1.1.6$ more /etc/init.d/postgresql-8.1 
#!/bin/sh -e

# Setting environment variables for the postmaster here does not work; please
# set them in /etc/postgresql/8.1/<cluster>/environment instead.

[ -r /usr/share/postgresql-common/init.d-functions ] || exit 0

. /usr/share/postgresql-common/init.d-functions

VERSION=8.1

case "$1" in
    start)
        start $VERSION
        ;;
    stop)
        stop "$VERSION"
        ;;
    restart)
        restart "$VERSION"
        ;;
    force-reload | reload)
        reload $VERSION
        ;;
    status)
        status $VERSION
        ;;
    autovac-start)
        autovac_start $VERSION
        ;;
    autovac-stop)
        autovac_stop $VERSION
        ;;
    autovac-restart)
        autovac_restart $VERSION
        ;;
    *)
        echo "Usage: $0 {start|stop|restart|reload|force-reload|status|autovac-start|autovac-stop|autovac-restart}"
        exit 1
        ;;
esac

exit 0
